<br>
80% of polled adults think you should be able to use marijuana legally for medical purposes.<br>
47% said they have tried marijuana at least once.<br>
72% say people arrested for possessing small amount of marijuana should be fined, not jailed.<br>
<br>
Can it kill you?<br>
&quot;No one has ever died of THC poisoning, mostly because a 160-lb person would have to smoke roughly 900 joints in a sitting to reach a lethal dose.&quot;<br>
<br>
Is it addictive?<br>
&quot;Yes. But the risk of becoming dependent on marijuana is low. Just 9% of those who have used the drug develope dependence. By comparison, 15% of drinkers become dependent on alcohol, 23% of heroin users get hooked, and a third of tobacco smokers become slaves to cigarettes.&quot;<br>
<br>
Does it make you stupid?<br>
&quot;Potheads are dumber than non-users, but only a little. Participants of a study who had used cannabis regularly for an average of 10 years fared significantly worse on only two of forty indices of cognitive functioning (they particularly had trouble estimating time passage). But scientists can't say that marijuana causes such problems, as the long-term users 'may have been worse off in the first place'.<br>
<br>
Can it give you cancer?<br>
&quot;The latest research suggests THC may have a dual effect, promoting tumors by increasing free radicals and simultaneously protecting against tumors by playing a beneficial role in the process known as programmed cell death.&quot;<br>
<br>
Do the sick really benefit?<br>
For HIV patients, marijuana is a godsend. HIV patients have a tendency to not want to eat and what is the number one thing pot does for you besides illicit a high? It gives you the munchies. Test subjects who smoked marijuana gained an average og 6.6 lbs. during a trial, compared with 2.4 lbs. for the group taking the placebo. Marijuana is also said to curtail nausea, glaucoma, spacticity (extreme muscle tension), and pain in general.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
You all know WHY pot was made Illegal in the first place right? William Randolph Hearst (Founder of the San Francisco Chronical) back in about the 1880's Rallied for Hemp and Marijuana to be made illegal, because he owned FORESTS of trees to cut down and make into paper. Yet Hemp/Marijunana was cheeper and easier to make paper. Theres your 2 bits of history. It wasn't banned due to drug use, it was banned because it was cheeper.  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
